<!-- begin paragraph -->
<tr>
<td width=3D"15%" valign=3D"top">
<!-- Add marginal notes below -->
<i>
<a name=3D"PPF">
Percent Point Function
</a>
</i>
</td>
<td valign=3D"TOP" width=3D"85%">
<!-- Add main text below -->
The Poisson percent point function does not exist in simple
closed form.  It is computed numerically.  Note that because
this is a discrete distribution that is only defined for integer
values of <i>x</i>, the percent point function is not smooth in the
way the percent point function typically is for a continuous
distribution.
<p>
The following is the plot of the Poisson percent point function
with the same values of <i>=CE=BB</i> as the pdf plots above.
</p><p>
<img src=3D"https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/eda/section3/gif/poipp=
f4.gif" alt=3D"plot of the Poisson percent point function">

</p></td>
</tr>
<!-- end paragraph -->

<!-- begin paragraph -->
<tr>
<td width=3D"15%" valign=3D"top">
<!-- Add marginal notes below -->
<i>
Common Statistics
</i>
</td>
<td valign=3D"TOP" width=3D"85%">
<!-- Add main text below -->
<table>

   <tbody><tr>
      <td valign=3D"top" width=3D"30%">
        Mean
      </td>
      <td valign=3D"top" width=3D"70%">
         <i>=CE=BB</i>
      </td>
    </tr>

   <tr>
      <td valign=3D"top" width=3D"30%">
        Mode
      </td>
      <td valign=3D"top" width=3D"70%">
         For non-integer <i>=CE=BB</i>, it is the largest integer less
         than <i>=CE=BB</i>.  For integer <i>=CE=BB</i>, <i>x</i>
         =3D <i>=CE=BB</i> and <i>x</i> =3D <i>=CE=BB</i> - 1 are both
         the mode.
      </td>
    </tr>

